3. Reshape the dataset by putting GDP values from different years into one variable(column)

data <- gather(data, key="Year", value="GDP", factor_key=TRUE,-CountryName, convert=TRUE)
head(data)
##   CountryName Year       GDP
## 1       Aruba 1960        NA
## 2 Afghanistan 1960 537777811
## 3      Angola 1960        NA
## 4     Albania 1960        NA
## 5     Andorra 1960        NA
## 6  Arab World 1960        NA

5. Extract the GDPs of Germany, France, Italy and Greece in the years 1960, 1970, 1980, 1990, 2000, 2010 and 2018

gdp.sub <- dplyr::filter(data, CountryName %in% c("France", "Germany", "Italy", "Greece"), Year %in% c(1960,1970,1980,1990,2000,2010,2018))

5.1 GDP trends in the countries

d <- ggplot(data=gdp.sub, aes(x=Year, y=GDP, color=CountryName))
d

d1 <- d + geom_point() + geom_line()
d1

d2 <- d1 + geom_text(aes(label=GDP))
d2

d2 <- d1 + geom_text(aes(label=GDP), hjust = 0.1, nudge_x = 0.05, size =2) + labs(title="GDP Trends in the Countries")
d2

5.2 Rescale the GDP by log2 and facet the plot by countries

d2 + scale_y_continuous(trans="log2") + facet_wrap(~CountryName)

d2 + scale_y_continuous(trans="log2") + facet_wrap(~CountryName, ncol=4)

5.3 Redo the plot using point + fitting with “loess” method

d + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="loess")

5.4 Area plot and “fill” to show the percentiles of the countries in different years

d + geom_area(aes(fill=CountryName), position="fill")

5.5 Use bar plot

d + geom_bar(stat="identity",aes(group=CountryName, fill=CountryName), position="dodge")

6. Show the GDP differences of the countries in 2018 on the map

eu_map <- map_data("world", region = c("France", "Germany", "Italy", "Greece"))

6.1 Plot the map using ggplot2 with geom_polygon (each country is a polygon)

p <- ggplot(eu_map, aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group)) + geom_polygon()
p

6.2 Change the color of each country in the map

p <- ggplot(eu_map, aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group)) + geom_polygon(aes(fill=region))
p

6.3 Merge the GDP data and map data

gdp.2018 <- dplyr::filter(gdp.sub, Year=="2018")
head(gdp.2018)
##   CountryName Year      GDP
## 1     Germany 2018 4.00e+12
## 2      France 2018 2.78e+12
## 3      Greece 2018 2.18e+11
## 4       Italy 2018 2.07e+12
gdp.map <- dplyr::left_join(eu_map, gdp.2018, by=c("region"="CountryName"))
head(gdp.map)
##       long      lat group order  region subregion Year   GDP

6.4 Use ggplot to color the countries based on their GDP values

x <- ggplot(gdp.map, aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group)) + geom_polygon(aes(fill=GDP))
x

6.5 Add the title and change the color scale with better labeling

x <- x + labs(title="2018 GPD in EU Countries")+ scale_fill_gradient(low="dark blue", high="red", breaks=c(1e+12,2e+12,3e+12), labels=c("1 Trillion","2 Trillion","3 Trillion"))
